 Glamorgan, Wales":"Coity, Glamorgan, Wales"},"en":{"1175–":"1175–Deceased","1161–Male":"1161–Deceased","1169–Male":"1169–Deceased","1173–Male":"1173–Deceased","1175–Male":"1175–Deceased","1176–Male":"1176–Deceased","1177–Male":"1177–Deceased","–Male":"Deceased","1180–Female":"1180–Deceased","1200–1281":"1200–1281","1219–Male":"1219–Deceased","–Female":"Deceased","1140–1207":"1140–1207","1140–1177":"1140–1177","1169":"1169","1200":"1200","1177":"1177","1176":"1176","1175":"1175","1140":"1140","1173":"1173","1161":"1161","1281":"1281","1219":"1219","1207":"1207","1180":"1180","Coity, Glamorgan, Wales":"Coity, Glamorgan, Wales","nameMeanings":[{"name":"De","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Turberville","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): habitational name, probably from Thouberville (Eure), or possibly from Trubleville (Seine-Maritime), both in France. The two may have been confused in surname usage."],"variants":[{"name":"Torbet","meanings":["Scottish:","from the Anglo-Norman and Middle English personal name <i>T(h)urbert</i>, <i>T(h)orbert</i>, a hybrid of Old Norse <i>Thorr</i> ‘Thor’, the name of the god of thunder, + ancient Germanic <i>-berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. The name was probably formed on the Continent; see   Turberville  .","perhaps in some cases a nickname from Old French and Middle English <i>turbot</i>, <i>turbut</i> ‘turbot’, for someone who caught or sold or resembled this fish."]},{"name":"Turbyfill","meanings":["Altered form of English   Turberville  ."]},{"name":"Tuberville","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Turberville  . This form of the surname is very rare in Britain and Ireland."]},{"name":"Turville","meanings":["English (Surrey and Hampshire; of Norman origin):","habitational name from Tourville‐la‐Campagne (Eure, France). The placename derives from the Old Norse personal name <i>Thórr</i> + Old French <i>ville</i> ‘farmstead, estate’ (from Latin <i>villa</i>).","occasionally a shortened form of   Turberville  ."]},{"name":"Turbeville","meanings":["English: variant of   Turberville  ."]},{"name":"Troublefield","meanings":["Probably an altered form of   Turberville  ."]}]},{"name":"Gilbert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Old French name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>gisil</i> ‘pledge’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. It was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. This was the name of the founder of the only native British religious order (abolished at the Dissolution of the Monasteries),  St Gilbert  of Sempringham (  ?1083–1189 ), in whose honour it is still sometimes bestowed, especially among Roman Catholics. It gained a wider currency in the 19th century."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Gilbert De Turberville II was born in 1175, in Coity, Glamorgan, Wales, his father, Pagamus De Turberville, was 35 and his mother, Sara verch Morgan of Glamorgan, was 36. He married Mallt Gam. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died in his hometown."},"et":{"1175–":"1175–Surnud","1161–Male":"1161–Surnud","1169–Male":"1169–Surnud","1173–Male":"1173–Surnud","1175–Male":"1175–Surnud","1176–Male":"1176–Surnud","1177–Male"